  <h>chrematonyms</h>
  <p>Chrematonyms are <a href="?xx=nouns/names">names</a> identifying scholarly and literary texts
    and other creative works, collections or archives.</p>
  <p>Like other kinds of name, chrematonyms can be classified into two grammatical types – <ul>
      <li>chrematonymic <a href="?xx=nouns/proper_nouns">proper nouns</a> – <g>Gairm</g>
        <en>[name of quarterly periodical]</en>, <g>Bannan</g>
        <en>[name of television drama serial]</en></li>
      <li>chrematonymic <a href="?xx=nouns/name_descriptions">name-descriptions</a> – <g>An
          Seann Tiomnadh</g>
        <en>The Old Testament</en>, <g>Òran na Cloiche</g>
        <en>The Song of the Stone [song title]</en>. </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <p>Note that chrematonyms (whether proper nouns or post-specified name-descriptions) are generally
      <emph>not lenited</emph> when they occur as (genitive) specifiers of another noun – <g>fear
      deasachaidh Gairm</g>
    <en>the editor of Gairm</en>, <g>oifis Tobar an Dualchais</g>
    <en>the Tobar an Dualchais office</en>, rather than <bad>fear deasachaidh Ghairm</bad>,
      <bad>oifis Thobar an Dualchais</bad>.</p>



